<p><b><a href="/wiki/War" title="War">War</a></b> – organised and often prolonged armed conflict that is carried out by <a href="/wiki/State_(polity)" title="State (polity)">states</a> and/or <a href="/wiki/Non-state_actors" title="Non-state actors" class="mw-redirect">non-state actors</a>. It is characterised by extreme <a href="/wiki/Violence" title="Violence">violence</a>, <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">social</a> disruption, and economic destruction.<sup id="cite_ref-AHD_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AHD-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-MWD_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MWD-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> War should be understood as an actual, intentional and widespread armed conflict between political communities, and therefore is defined as a form of <a href="/wiki/Political_violence" title="Political violence">political violence</a> or <a href="/wiki/Interventionism_(politics)" title="Interventionism (politics)">intervention</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-AHD_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AHD-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> The set of techniques used by a group to carry out war is known as <b>warfare</b>. An absence of war is usually called <a href="/wiki/Peace" title="Peace">peace</a>.</p>
<div class="toclimit-2">
